1
00:00:04,571 --> 00:00:08,475
<i>Your son shoplifted from my store.</i>

2
00:00:08,541 --> 00:00:10,744
We shouldn't let him
manipulate us any further.

3
00:00:10,810 --> 00:00:12,712
<i>What is he demanding?</i>

4
00:00:12,779 --> 00:00:15,482
<i>The victim is Hideyuki Sakuma,</i>
<i>40 years old.</i>

5
00:00:15,548 --> 00:00:18,184
The manager of Smile Sakuma
in Mitsuba Minami.

6
00:00:18,251 --> 00:00:20,186
The bullet extracted from the body

7
00:00:20,253 --> 00:00:23,690
<i>was fired from the gun that belonged</i>
<i>to Keisuke's father.</i>

8
00:00:24,524 --> 00:00:26,126
I killed my older brother.

9
00:00:26,192 --> 00:00:28,628
<i>Mr. Naoto Sakuma just confessed</i>
<i>to the crime.</i>

10
00:00:28,695 --> 00:00:30,130
<i>But since you were his classmate,</i>

11
00:00:30,196 --> 00:00:32,599
<i>you will not be allowed</i>
<i>to join the questioning.</i>

12
00:00:32,665 --> 00:00:33,733
<i>Please come here.</i>

13
00:00:35,068 --> 00:00:37,737
Please come here right now, Junichi.

14
00:00:38,238 --> 00:00:41,374
Did he say where he found the gun?

15
00:00:41,441 --> 00:00:43,510
He said he found it

16
00:00:44,310 --> 00:00:45,211
<i>in the forest.</i>

17
00:00:46,713 --> 00:00:49,649
I opened the time capsule,
but there was no gun inside.

18
00:00:49,716 --> 00:00:52,786
<i>I asked you when you took the gun</i>
<i>from the time capsule.</i>

19
00:00:52,852 --> 00:00:56,689
The gun that wasn't there on Friday night
was there on Saturday night?

20
00:00:57,257 --> 00:01:00,026
<i>Did you really dig up that time capsule</i>
<i>on Saturday night?</i>

21
00:01:00,960 --> 00:01:01,795
<i>I too…</i>

22
00:01:05,899 --> 00:01:08,168
have something I've been shouldering.

23
00:01:16,109 --> 00:01:17,444
<i>Why didn't you</i>

24
00:01:18,511 --> 00:01:20,480
<i>contact Maki after we all graduated?</i>

25
00:01:21,681 --> 00:01:24,150
<i>Isn't it because</i>
<i>you were shouldering something</i>

26
00:01:25,718 --> 00:01:27,654
<i>that you'll never be able to escape from?</i>

27
00:01:30,023 --> 00:01:31,524
<i>It's okay</i>

28
00:01:33,960 --> 00:01:36,262
<i>to be freed from what you did</i>

29
00:01:36,830 --> 00:01:37,697
<i>23 years ago.</i>

30
00:01:37,764 --> 00:01:40,100
<i>What the heck are you talking about?</i>

31
00:01:41,301 --> 00:01:42,402
On that day…

32
00:01:44,504 --> 00:01:45,805
I saw it…

33
00:02:01,754 --> 00:02:02,922
I saw you

34
00:02:04,891 --> 00:02:07,060
shoot someone with a gun.

35
00:02:20,273 --> 00:02:21,207
<i>Until now</i>

36
00:02:22,308 --> 00:02:24,244
<i>I've kept it locked away in my heart,</i>

37
00:02:24,911 --> 00:02:26,913
and it will remain locked away forever.

38
00:02:29,082 --> 00:02:30,283
I will

39
00:02:32,819 --> 00:02:34,354
protect you, Junichi.

40
00:03:06,753 --> 00:03:08,621
Tobina. Hey there.

41
00:03:12,392 --> 00:03:13,393
Tobina.

42
00:03:13,459 --> 00:03:14,861
Can we talk a little?

43
00:03:15,361 --> 00:03:19,566
MITSUBA POLICE STATION

44
00:03:19,632 --> 00:03:20,700
Come inside.

45
00:03:21,234 --> 00:03:24,704
You must be devastated that Naoto Sakuma
has become a suspect.

46
00:03:27,340 --> 00:03:28,975
It’s hard on me too.

47
00:03:32,545 --> 00:03:33,379
What?

48
00:03:36,082 --> 00:03:37,250
The truth is,

49
00:03:37,317 --> 00:03:39,752
during the incident 23 years ago,

50
00:03:39,819 --> 00:03:41,921
I was working here,

51
00:03:42,689 --> 00:03:46,326
<i>and I saw the four of you being helped</i>
<i>by the police.</i>

52
00:03:48,895 --> 00:03:51,231
I wanted the future to be bright

53
00:03:51,297 --> 00:03:53,900
for the four children who had gone through

54
00:03:55,001 --> 00:03:56,903
such a shocking experience.

55
00:03:58,037 --> 00:03:59,839
That was my sincere wish.

56
00:04:03,543 --> 00:04:07,680
When you appeared in front of me
as a police officer,

57
00:04:09,782 --> 00:04:11,584
I was really surprised.

58
00:04:15,755 --> 00:04:16,656
I'm proud of you

59
00:04:17,557 --> 00:04:19,325
for becoming a police officer.

60
00:04:24,597 --> 00:04:27,467
It must be difficult for you to accept
that your classmate

61
00:04:27,533 --> 00:04:29,269
has committed a crime,

62
00:04:30,270 --> 00:04:32,538
but I hope you will properly fulfill

63
00:04:33,473 --> 00:04:35,041
your duties as a police officer.

64
00:04:38,211 --> 00:04:39,045
Yes, sir.

65
00:04:43,249 --> 00:04:44,384
Good morning.

66
00:04:44,450 --> 00:04:45,451
Good morning.

67
00:04:46,786 --> 00:04:48,821
No matter what you order,
we'll split the check.

68
00:04:51,424 --> 00:04:52,258
Okay.

69
00:05:01,467 --> 00:05:02,402
What brings you here?

70
00:05:03,236 --> 00:05:05,905
There are several things
that have been bothering me,

71
00:05:05,972 --> 00:05:08,608
so I figured I’d think about them
in a different setting.

72
00:05:12,078 --> 00:05:13,279
What's bothering you?

73
00:05:14,614 --> 00:05:15,615
Number one.

74
00:05:16,983 --> 00:05:19,185
According to Naoto Sakuma's testimony,

75
00:05:19,252 --> 00:05:21,888
his older brother, Hideyuki,

76
00:05:21,954 --> 00:05:23,756
found the gun in the forest,

77
00:05:24,457 --> 00:05:27,894
but I can't imagine
how he could have possibly found it there.

78
00:05:29,996 --> 00:05:32,231
Detective Tobina, can you imagine

79
00:05:32,732 --> 00:05:37,537
when and in what situation
he picked up Officer Kiyohara's gun?

80
00:05:37,603 --> 00:05:40,573
I agree, that's difficult to imagine.

81
00:05:40,640 --> 00:05:41,808
Number two.

82
00:05:43,076 --> 00:05:46,079
On the day Hideyuki Sakuma was murdered,

83
00:05:46,145 --> 00:05:52,118
Makiko Iwamoto and Keisuke Kiyohara
reportedly met here at 8:00 p.m.,

84
00:05:52,185 --> 00:05:53,553
then went separate ways,

85
00:05:53,619 --> 00:05:56,489
and met again two hours later.

86
00:05:56,556 --> 00:05:59,025
However, it seems strange that they would

87
00:05:59,092 --> 00:06:01,327
arrange to meet twice
at this same restaurant.

88
00:06:01,394 --> 00:06:03,029
Please get that for me.

89
00:06:03,963 --> 00:06:05,098
Sure.

90
00:06:09,168 --> 00:06:10,436
During those two hours,

91
00:06:10,503 --> 00:06:13,373
Keisuke Kiyohara checked into his hotel,

92
00:06:13,439 --> 00:06:16,576
and Makiko Iwamoto returned
to the hair salon.

93
00:06:17,543 --> 00:06:21,481
We have confirmed that Keisuke Kiyohara
checked into the hotel, right?

94
00:06:21,547 --> 00:06:22,382
Yes.

95
00:06:23,282 --> 00:06:24,784
Regarding Makiko Iwamoto,

96
00:06:24,851 --> 00:06:26,119
<i>there were two witnesses</i>

97
00:06:26,185 --> 00:06:28,888
<i>stating that the lights were on</i>
<i>at the salon and they saw a figure inside.</i>

98
00:06:29,389 --> 00:06:31,090
A figure inside, huh?

99
00:06:33,326 --> 00:06:34,227
Yes.

100
00:06:34,293 --> 00:06:35,561
Number three.

101
00:06:37,930 --> 00:06:39,031
We'll talk about that

102
00:06:39,932 --> 00:06:42,668
when I get everyone together again.

103
00:06:53,179 --> 00:06:55,214
Detective Ayanokoji,
would you like some too?

104
00:06:56,449 --> 00:06:57,950
Ayanokoji…

105
00:06:58,651 --> 00:07:00,887
Are you doing it on purpose?

106
00:07:01,621 --> 00:07:02,855
But I don't mind.

107
00:07:02,922 --> 00:07:04,857
I actually kind of like it.

108
00:07:04,924 --> 00:07:05,925
It’s ripe.

109
00:07:07,093 --> 00:07:09,562
Yes. I, Nagai, will gladly accept.

110
00:07:10,496 --> 00:07:11,397
Did you know

111
00:07:11,464 --> 00:07:13,332
if you peel it into three sections
you're a monkey?

112
00:07:13,399 --> 00:07:16,869
But if you peel it into four sections,
you're a human!

113
00:07:16,936 --> 00:07:17,804
Just kidding!

114
00:07:19,739 --> 00:07:21,007
It's pretty darn good.

115
00:07:21,507 --> 00:07:22,775
Delicious.

116
00:07:23,976 --> 00:07:24,977
What?

117
00:07:33,786 --> 00:07:36,055
MIHO

118
00:07:37,023 --> 00:07:37,957
Hello?

119
00:07:38,024 --> 00:07:38,858
<i>Manager.</i>

120
00:07:40,259 --> 00:07:41,794
I'm so sorry!

121
00:07:41,861 --> 00:07:43,996
<i>What's the matter?</i>

122
00:07:44,063 --> 00:07:45,064
I…

123
00:07:45,565 --> 00:07:49,836
sometimes use the salon at night
without your permission.

124
00:07:50,536 --> 00:07:51,904
What do you mean?

125
00:07:53,339 --> 00:07:54,173
<i>At night,</i>

126
00:07:55,107 --> 00:07:57,777
<i>I sometimes cut and dye</i>
<i>my boyfriend's hair.</i>

127
00:08:00,680 --> 00:08:01,881
I see.

128
00:08:01,948 --> 00:08:03,816
I was using it again today

129
00:08:04,884 --> 00:08:06,452
and when I was about to leave,

130
00:08:07,487 --> 00:08:09,355
<i>the police came.</i>

131
00:08:09,922 --> 00:08:10,723
What?

132
00:08:11,290 --> 00:08:13,860
<i>The police asked me</i>
<i>when I was at the salon at night,</i>

133
00:08:14,994 --> 00:08:16,395
<i>and I told them.</i>

134
00:08:19,532 --> 00:08:20,366
Hey…

135
00:08:22,735 --> 00:08:24,470
When was the last time you used it?

136
00:08:25,438 --> 00:08:27,807
Saturday, the 17th.

137
00:08:30,443 --> 00:08:32,178
<i>I'm really sorry!</i>

138
00:08:37,583 --> 00:08:38,985
It's all right.

139
00:08:39,051 --> 00:08:40,152
<i>Sorry.</i>

140
00:08:41,854 --> 00:08:42,722
Bye.

141
00:09:29,802 --> 00:09:31,470
Sorry, did I wake you?

142
00:09:37,276 --> 00:09:38,744
Junichi.

143
00:09:45,751 --> 00:09:46,919
It's decaf.

144
00:09:51,157 --> 00:09:52,325
Thanks.

145
00:10:06,072 --> 00:10:07,340
Hiromi,

146
00:10:09,875 --> 00:10:11,978
why did you decide to become a nurse?

147
00:10:12,044 --> 00:10:12,878
What?

148
00:10:14,146 --> 00:10:16,782
I just thought it was an unusual question.

149
00:10:17,717 --> 00:10:19,986
Since it involves
matters of life and death,

150
00:10:21,988 --> 00:10:24,190
I wondered if it was your wish
to help people.

151
00:10:28,127 --> 00:10:29,295
You know…

152
00:10:29,362 --> 00:10:30,196
Yeah?

153
00:10:32,298 --> 00:10:35,334
I've never felt any desire to help

154
00:10:36,002 --> 00:10:39,205
or to empathize with my patients at all.

155
00:10:39,271 --> 00:10:40,306
What?

156
00:10:40,373 --> 00:10:42,441
But I'm

157
00:10:43,342 --> 00:10:45,578
friendly enough,

158
00:10:46,145 --> 00:10:49,048
so I'm often mistaken for
a nurse who cares for her patients.

159
00:10:49,115 --> 00:10:50,783
It's not true?

160
00:10:51,484 --> 00:10:52,918
Yeah.

161
00:10:53,786 --> 00:10:54,854
What about you, Junichi?

162
00:10:54,920 --> 00:10:57,123
Why did you become a police officer?

163
00:11:02,328 --> 00:11:04,163
I shouldn't have become one.

164
00:11:05,031 --> 00:11:06,265
Why?

165
00:11:07,800 --> 00:11:09,635
Because I've committed a crime.

166
00:11:12,371 --> 00:11:13,406
Like what?

167
00:11:17,910 --> 00:11:18,911
What do you think?

168
00:11:24,050 --> 00:11:25,551
Did you eat all the Alaskan pink shrimp

169
00:11:26,318 --> 00:11:28,287
at a sushi restaurant?

170
00:11:32,591 --> 00:11:34,160
- Oh, I know.
- Okay.

171
00:11:35,461 --> 00:11:37,063
A girl did everything

172
00:11:38,064 --> 00:11:42,034
to express her feelings for you,
but you pretended not to notice.

173
00:11:42,101 --> 00:11:44,537
- I think I'm guilty of doing that.
- I knew it.

174
00:11:44,603 --> 00:11:47,106
Also, I ate the leftover flan
from the school lunch even though

175
00:11:47,173 --> 00:11:49,108
we were supposed to win it
by playing a game.

176
00:11:49,608 --> 00:11:51,610
I can totally picture that in my head.

177
00:11:55,081 --> 00:11:56,882
In the second year of high school…

178
00:11:56,949 --> 00:11:57,783
Yeah?

179
00:11:58,617 --> 00:12:01,987
I happened to see a poster
for the police officer recruitment exam.

180
00:12:02,054 --> 00:12:05,024
You just happened to see it?
And so you became a police officer?

181
00:12:05,091 --> 00:12:06,225
You know,

182
00:12:07,760 --> 00:12:09,562
my father died when I was in kindergarten.

183
00:12:12,231 --> 00:12:14,400
I didn't have much money,

184
00:12:15,367 --> 00:12:17,703
so I worked at a car repair shop
during the day

185
00:12:17,770 --> 00:12:19,739
and took high school classes at night.

186
00:12:20,239 --> 00:12:22,808
I saw that poster
on the school bulletin board,

187
00:12:25,077 --> 00:12:26,879
and thought that being a civil servant

188
00:12:28,080 --> 00:12:29,682
would be a nice, stable job.

189
00:12:35,054 --> 00:12:36,155
But, you know,

190
00:12:37,723 --> 00:12:39,391
when I was in elementary school,

191
00:12:40,559 --> 00:12:42,962
I had a friend whose dad
played catch with me,

192
00:12:43,028 --> 00:12:45,531
and taught me kendo.

193
00:12:46,532 --> 00:12:48,000
I was really attached to him,

194
00:12:49,435 --> 00:12:51,537
<i>and I called him "Pops."</i>

195
00:12:52,404 --> 00:12:54,974
That person was a police officer.

196
00:12:55,608 --> 00:12:56,509
Wow.

197
00:12:59,945 --> 00:13:03,916
Does Pops know

198
00:13:04,450 --> 00:13:07,019
that you became a police officer?

199
00:13:09,555 --> 00:13:10,389
No.

200
00:13:13,058 --> 00:13:14,627
Pops

201
00:13:15,961 --> 00:13:18,397
was killed by a robber when I was in

202
00:13:20,399 --> 00:13:22,301
the sixth grade of elementary school,

203
00:13:25,237 --> 00:13:27,506
and I was the first person
to discover his body.

204
00:13:32,978 --> 00:13:35,748
Maybe it's not just by chance
that you became a police officer.

205
00:13:41,220 --> 00:13:42,054
Right?

206
00:13:43,088 --> 00:13:44,557
Yeah.

207
00:13:50,362 --> 00:13:53,165
MAKIKO IWAMOTO

208
00:13:53,933 --> 00:13:54,800
Hello?

209
00:13:58,571 --> 00:14:00,306
Sorry to call at this hour.

210
00:14:02,474 --> 00:14:03,375
What's the matter?

211
00:14:15,221 --> 00:14:17,223
Good morning, Ms. Iwamoto.

212
00:14:17,289 --> 00:14:18,724
Good morning.

213
00:14:18,791 --> 00:14:20,226
I have something I'd like to ask you.

214
00:14:20,292 --> 00:14:22,094
Would you mind coming
to the police station?

215
00:14:24,129 --> 00:14:25,631
You want me to come voluntarily?

216
00:14:25,698 --> 00:14:26,532
Yes.

217
00:14:28,634 --> 00:14:29,668
Then I decline.

218
00:14:30,302 --> 00:14:31,303
What?

219
00:14:31,804 --> 00:14:33,038
I have work to attend to.

220
00:14:33,105 --> 00:14:34,273
You're going to evade us?

221
00:14:37,209 --> 00:14:38,444
Excuse me.

222
00:14:53,859 --> 00:14:54,793
Wow.

223
00:15:02,401 --> 00:15:03,802
I asked her to leave.

224
00:15:18,617 --> 00:15:20,452
Thank you for coming.

225
00:15:22,488 --> 00:15:23,322
But

226
00:15:24,356 --> 00:15:25,291
I'm sorry.

227
00:15:27,192 --> 00:15:28,127
I can't

228
00:15:28,928 --> 00:15:30,229
tell you anything right now.

229
00:15:31,397 --> 00:15:32,231
Not even to me?

230
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:36,602
Sorry. I can't right now.

231
00:15:40,205 --> 00:15:41,106
Okay.

232
00:16:00,626 --> 00:16:01,460
Hey.

233
00:16:04,496 --> 00:16:05,631
Junichi,

234
00:16:08,200 --> 00:16:09,802
can you talk about it now?

235
00:16:12,738 --> 00:16:13,672
About what?

236
00:16:18,811 --> 00:16:20,846
Right after you graduated,

237
00:16:21,947 --> 00:16:24,350
you moved to Yokohama.

238
00:16:25,184 --> 00:16:26,018
Yeah.

239
00:16:27,319 --> 00:16:28,654
When I told you

240
00:16:29,722 --> 00:16:32,024
that I'd come to see you off
on your last day,

241
00:16:32,791 --> 00:16:35,594
you said, "Don't you dare come."
Do you remember that?

242
00:16:38,964 --> 00:16:41,967
Since you said, "Don't you dare come,"

243
00:16:42,468 --> 00:16:45,104
I asked you to keep in touch,

244
00:16:46,071 --> 00:16:47,706
and you said you wouldn't.

245
00:16:52,578 --> 00:16:53,912
Why was that?

246
00:16:56,582 --> 00:16:57,850
Did I say that?

247
00:16:58,417 --> 00:17:00,285
You don't remember?

248
00:17:00,352 --> 00:17:01,186
Yeah.

249
00:17:02,921 --> 00:17:06,291
Back then,
I thought I was going to marry you,

250
00:17:06,358 --> 00:17:08,260
so it was a huge shock to me.

251
00:17:18,737 --> 00:17:21,206
But you got mad at me for kissing you?

252
00:17:22,674 --> 00:17:24,610
Well, that's because…

253
00:17:28,147 --> 00:17:30,482
that was not the right place
or the right time.

254
00:17:39,091 --> 00:17:40,159
Thank you.

255
00:17:43,562 --> 00:17:44,830
I promise

256
00:17:45,798 --> 00:17:47,599
I won't cause you any trouble.

257
00:17:55,407 --> 00:17:57,076
I guess I already am.

258
00:18:08,887 --> 00:18:09,721
I'll be off.

259
00:18:13,525 --> 00:18:14,359
Bye.

260
00:18:50,929 --> 00:18:52,364
<i>It's tomorrow at ten, right?</i>

261
00:18:53,932 --> 00:18:55,467
Don't come to see me off.

262
00:18:56,702 --> 00:18:57,636
Why?

263
00:18:57,703 --> 00:18:58,904
You don't have to come.

264
00:19:03,075 --> 00:19:03,976
Because you'll cry?

265
00:19:04,042 --> 00:19:05,010
<i>No way.</i>

266
00:19:07,713 --> 00:19:09,114
Keep in touch even after you move.

267
00:19:09,181 --> 00:19:10,315
I won't.

268
00:19:11,517 --> 00:19:13,352
- Why?
- Just shut up.

269
00:19:15,320 --> 00:19:16,655
I won't see you ever again.

270
00:19:51,023 --> 00:19:52,224
Ms. Nara,

271
00:19:52,291 --> 00:19:54,593
I've never had anyone refuse
voluntary accompaniment.

272
00:19:54,660 --> 00:19:55,627
Seriously.

273
00:19:56,662 --> 00:19:58,363
Let's tell Naoto Sakuma that her alibi

274
00:19:58,430 --> 00:20:00,499
has fallen apart and see how he reacts.

275
00:20:02,234 --> 00:20:04,369
That's a no, huh? Sorry.

276
00:20:05,771 --> 00:20:09,141
I wonder if we'll ever find the gun.

277
00:20:09,208 --> 00:20:11,310
The gun that Naoto Sakuma
threw into the river?

278
00:20:13,011 --> 00:20:14,713
I wonder…

279
00:20:14,780 --> 00:20:16,748
Mr. Tobina! We have crazy news.

280
00:20:16,815 --> 00:20:19,851
Makiko Iwamoto
declined to accompany us voluntarily.

281
00:20:20,419 --> 00:20:21,420
Isn't that crazy?

282
00:20:21,920 --> 00:20:23,121
It's crazy, right?

283
00:20:23,188 --> 00:20:25,524
I never even imagined she'd decline.

284
00:20:25,591 --> 00:20:27,926
I didn't know you could
decline voluntary accompaniment.

285
00:20:27,993 --> 00:20:30,529
- Detective Tobina.
- Yes?

286
00:20:31,096 --> 00:20:33,699
I told you that something
has been bothering me, right?

287
00:20:34,199 --> 00:20:36,235
The one you'll tell us
when everyone is together?

288
00:20:36,301 --> 00:20:37,169
Everyone?

289
00:20:37,236 --> 00:20:38,070
Yes.

290
00:20:38,570 --> 00:20:40,606
Let's all go find the gun together.

291
00:20:40,672 --> 00:20:41,907
Together?

292
00:20:41,974 --> 00:20:44,309
The key to solving this case is that gun.

293
00:20:44,376 --> 00:20:45,444
The key?

294
00:20:45,944 --> 00:20:49,248
However, this will be done secretly
by Detective Tobina and me,

295
00:20:49,314 --> 00:20:51,683
without the Special Investigation
Headquarters.

296
00:20:53,885 --> 00:20:55,821
The buddy cop returns!

297
00:21:06,832 --> 00:21:08,867
<i>The search in the river is continuing,</i>

298
00:21:09,434 --> 00:21:13,272
but everyone is predicting
that the gun won't be found.

299
00:21:14,239 --> 00:21:15,474
I see.

300
00:21:15,974 --> 00:21:16,975
It seems

301
00:21:17,042 --> 00:21:20,712
the prefectural police are trying to close
the case by identifying

302
00:21:21,680 --> 00:21:23,815
Naoto Sakuma as the culprit,
while withholding

303
00:21:24,316 --> 00:21:26,852
that the gun involved
was a police-issued firearm.

304
00:21:29,821 --> 00:21:31,456
I understand.

305
00:21:31,990 --> 00:21:35,160
I will go along with that narrative.

306
00:21:43,068 --> 00:21:45,837
I wonder where that gun went.

307
00:21:53,111 --> 00:21:55,580
Mr. Kiyohara and Ms. Iwamoto,

308
00:21:55,647 --> 00:21:58,784
thank you so much
for coming all the way here.

309
00:22:00,585 --> 00:22:02,287
I asked you all to gather here

310
00:22:02,354 --> 00:22:04,122
because I want to re-examine

311
00:22:04,189 --> 00:22:06,491
the incident that happened 23 years ago.

312
00:22:07,893 --> 00:22:09,695
As I mentioned before,

313
00:22:09,761 --> 00:22:11,563
a long time has passed since then.

314
00:22:11,630 --> 00:22:12,931
My memory is vague.

315
00:22:12,998 --> 00:22:15,133
It'll be difficult
to help re-examine anything.

316
00:22:15,200 --> 00:22:17,803
You're absolutely right, Mr. Kiyohara.

317
00:22:18,470 --> 00:22:22,074
Memory is something that can change.

318
00:22:22,674 --> 00:22:23,942
Nevertheless,

319
00:22:24,009 --> 00:22:25,977
I don't think it's a waste of time

320
00:22:26,545 --> 00:22:28,947
for you all,
who were children at the time,

321
00:22:29,014 --> 00:22:31,483
to re-examine the situation now as adults.

322
00:22:32,250 --> 00:22:36,154
Coming to this place
might bring back some memories.

323
00:22:36,221 --> 00:22:38,890
There are things I don't want to remember.

324
00:22:38,957 --> 00:22:39,791
Yes.

325
00:22:41,193 --> 00:22:43,962
I understand this will bring back
painful memories.

326
00:22:44,463 --> 00:22:45,464
However,

327
00:22:46,031 --> 00:22:49,334
this concerns your father's gun.

328
00:22:49,401 --> 00:22:51,870
We would appreciate your cooperation.

329
00:22:52,971 --> 00:22:56,108
Now, if you remember
where you guys entered from,

330
00:22:56,174 --> 00:22:58,310
please tell me.

331
00:22:59,211 --> 00:23:00,212
This way.

332
00:23:02,447 --> 00:23:03,448
Let's go.

333
00:23:40,252 --> 00:23:41,420
<i>Naoto!</i>

334
00:23:44,055 --> 00:23:45,257
I'll go look for Naoto.

335
00:23:45,323 --> 00:23:46,558
Okay.

336
00:23:49,528 --> 00:23:50,796
Naoto!

337
00:24:05,710 --> 00:24:08,313
CAUTION
BEYOND THIS POINT IS EXTREMELY DANGEROUS

338
00:24:08,380 --> 00:24:10,982
PLEASE REFRAIN FROM ENTERING
UNLESS YOU ARE AUTHORIZED TO DO SO

339
00:24:27,699 --> 00:24:29,034
BEWARE OF FALLING ROCKS

340
00:24:29,100 --> 00:24:30,469
NO TRESPASSING

341
00:24:57,395 --> 00:24:58,263
<i>You shouldn't go.</i>

342
00:24:58,897 --> 00:24:59,965
Don't go there.

343
00:25:01,132 --> 00:25:01,967
Don't go.

344
00:25:17,649 --> 00:25:21,319
BEWARE OF FALLING ROCKS

345
00:25:57,589 --> 00:26:00,725
This is where we found
Officer Kiyohara's body.

346
00:26:02,327 --> 00:26:06,031
Exactly where was Officer Kiyohara's body
when you found him?

347
00:26:07,465 --> 00:26:08,500
Over there.

348
00:26:10,201 --> 00:26:13,204
Where was the body of Oshima,
the perpetrator?

349
00:26:18,910 --> 00:26:19,911
<i>Over there.</i>

350
00:26:30,322 --> 00:26:32,424
According to the investigation reports,

351
00:26:32,490 --> 00:26:38,430
the four of you went into the forest
to catch freshwater crabs in the creek.

352
00:26:39,564 --> 00:26:41,199
You guys heard several gunshots

353
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:44,302
and got scared, so you tried to run away.

354
00:26:45,103 --> 00:26:48,840
While running away, all of you discovered
the body of Officer Kiyohara,

355
00:26:48,907 --> 00:26:51,309
and immediately tried to leave the forest.

356
00:26:53,044 --> 00:26:54,312
Is that correct?

357
00:26:57,515 --> 00:26:58,783
<i>That's correct.</i>

358
00:26:58,850 --> 00:27:02,153
Mr. Keisuke Kiyohara, is that correct?

359
00:27:03,288 --> 00:27:04,122
<i>Yes.</i>

360
00:27:05,323 --> 00:27:06,992
And you, Mr. Naoto Sakuma?

361
00:27:08,226 --> 00:27:09,394
<i>That's correct.</i>

362
00:27:09,461 --> 00:27:11,129
Ms. Makiko Iwamoto?

363
00:27:11,630 --> 00:27:13,531
<i>That's correct.</i>

364
00:27:19,504 --> 00:27:22,140
What I just mentioned
are the only things recorded

365
00:27:23,041 --> 00:27:24,442
in the investigation reports.

366
00:27:25,143 --> 00:27:26,978
Even though it was such a major incident,

367
00:27:27,846 --> 00:27:31,816
and you four
were the first to discover the body,

368
00:27:31,883 --> 00:27:34,119
the report was far too concise,

369
00:27:34,953 --> 00:27:37,889
or in other words, poorly written.

370
00:27:38,623 --> 00:27:43,828
Therefore, I'd like
to re-examine it again in more detail.

371
00:27:45,330 --> 00:27:50,835
Let's start with the location
where you all heard the gunshots.

372
00:27:51,469 --> 00:27:56,708
Let's start with the location
where you all heard the gunshots.

373
00:27:57,509 --> 00:28:00,612
Where did you hear the first gunshot?

374
00:28:02,747 --> 00:28:05,417
I believe the road
was split into two back there,

375
00:28:06,117 --> 00:28:07,185
but Makiko…

376
00:28:09,421 --> 00:28:12,157
- Ms. Iwamoto and I--
- Just call her how you usually do.

377
00:28:13,525 --> 00:28:14,693
Makiko and I

378
00:28:15,260 --> 00:28:17,429
took the road to the right
and heard the gunshot.

379
00:28:18,863 --> 00:28:22,300
So, the four of you weren't together
the whole time?

380
00:28:23,401 --> 00:28:24,235
Correct.

381
00:28:24,836 --> 00:28:27,939
We split into two groups
and planned to meet up at the river.

382
00:28:28,506 --> 00:28:31,142
So then Mr. Kiyohara
and Mr. Sakuma were together?

383
00:28:31,910 --> 00:28:32,744
Yes.

384
00:28:33,878 --> 00:28:38,383
Then Mr. Kiyohara,
where did you hear the gunshot?

385
00:28:41,486 --> 00:28:42,821
<i>Naoto and I</i>

386
00:28:42,887 --> 00:28:45,824
heard it while walking
on the path we were just on.

387
00:28:47,726 --> 00:28:49,394
We first heard one gunshot.

388
00:28:57,102 --> 00:28:58,369
<i>Then after that,</i>

389
00:28:58,903 --> 00:29:00,772
we heard two more gunshots.

390
00:29:01,506 --> 00:29:04,309
Then, we immediately returned
the way we came.

391
00:29:04,375 --> 00:29:05,376
NO TRESPASSING

392
00:29:08,179 --> 00:29:10,014
Keisuke, what's wrong?

393
00:29:10,081 --> 00:29:12,083
<i>When I met up with Junichi and Makiko</i>

394
00:29:12,150 --> 00:29:14,352
at the fork in the road,

395
00:29:14,419 --> 00:29:16,154
we heard one more gunshot.

396
00:29:16,721 --> 00:29:17,789
Where's Naoto?

397
00:29:17,856 --> 00:29:19,557
What? He's right behind me.

398
00:29:20,058 --> 00:29:21,626
- Where's Naoto?
- What?

399
00:29:21,693 --> 00:29:22,827
NO TRESPASSING

400
00:29:23,394 --> 00:29:26,264
So you heard four gunshots
up to that point.

401
00:29:26,831 --> 00:29:27,832
Yes.

402
00:29:27,899 --> 00:29:28,900
Then what happened?

403
00:29:30,201 --> 00:29:32,971
I thought Naoto was behind me,
but he wasn't,

404
00:29:34,005 --> 00:29:36,207
so Junichi went to look for him.

405
00:29:38,042 --> 00:29:39,077
As Makiko and I

406
00:29:39,978 --> 00:29:42,847
were leaving the forest
to call the police,

407
00:29:43,615 --> 00:29:45,083
we heard another gunshot.

408
00:29:49,287 --> 00:29:51,322
That was the last gunshot I heard.

409
00:29:51,890 --> 00:29:55,927
So there were five gunshots in total.

410
00:29:55,994 --> 00:29:56,828
Yes.

411
00:29:57,328 --> 00:29:58,196
Then what happened?

412
00:29:58,763 --> 00:30:00,899
I was worried about Junichi and Naoto,

413
00:30:01,399 --> 00:30:03,134
so instead of leaving the forest,

414
00:30:03,635 --> 00:30:05,103
Makiko and I went back.

415
00:30:07,672 --> 00:30:09,474
<i>We first found Naoto.</i>

416
00:30:11,643 --> 00:30:13,745
<i>I was about to go in the direction</i>
<i>Junichi had gone,</i>

417
00:30:14,245 --> 00:30:16,314
when he came back.

418
00:30:18,016 --> 00:30:20,018
<i>I could tell something was wrong</i>
<i>with Junichi,</i>

419
00:30:22,453 --> 00:30:24,322
<i>so I wondered what had happened,</i>

420
00:30:27,692 --> 00:30:28,893
and went to go see…

421
00:30:29,894 --> 00:30:32,263
You found Officer Kiyohara's body.

422
00:30:32,997 --> 00:30:34,399
Correct?

423
00:30:35,700 --> 00:30:36,534
Yes.

424
00:30:37,802 --> 00:30:39,103
Thank you.

425
00:30:40,004 --> 00:30:42,674
What do you remember, Ms. Iwamoto?

426
00:30:45,810 --> 00:30:46,845
It's just as he mentioned.

427
00:30:49,113 --> 00:30:50,081
Mr. Sakuma?

428
00:30:53,985 --> 00:30:56,754
What do you remember, Mr. Sakuma?

429
00:30:59,557 --> 00:31:02,894
I was so scared I couldn't even move.

430
00:31:03,695 --> 00:31:06,464
I don't even remember where or how many
shots there were.

431
00:31:07,899 --> 00:31:08,766
And then?

432
00:31:10,902 --> 00:31:12,036
All four of us

433
00:31:13,271 --> 00:31:14,839
went towards the sound of the gunshot…

434
00:31:14,906 --> 00:31:16,541
I saw it…

435
00:31:17,108 --> 00:31:18,343
…and found Keisuke's father.

436
00:31:19,310 --> 00:31:20,511
Thank you.

437
00:31:22,413 --> 00:31:25,049
Now, Detective Tobina…

438
00:31:27,218 --> 00:31:28,753
Detective Tobina!

439
00:31:28,820 --> 00:31:31,256
Tell us where you heard the shots
and how many you heard.

440
00:31:32,924 --> 00:31:36,261
<i>Makiko and I took the path to the right.</i>

441
00:31:38,963 --> 00:31:39,864
<i>First, we heard one shot.</i>

442
00:31:40,932 --> 00:31:42,767
<i>Then we heard two more gunshots.</i>

443
00:31:44,402 --> 00:31:45,970
We returned to the fork in the road,

444
00:31:47,305 --> 00:31:49,374
and when we reunited with Keisuke,
we heard one more shot.

445
00:31:49,440 --> 00:31:50,675
Then,

446
00:31:51,175 --> 00:31:53,811
you went down the left path
to look for Mr. Sakuma.

447
00:31:54,412 --> 00:31:55,980
Is that correct?

448
00:31:57,482 --> 00:31:58,316
Yes.

449
00:31:58,816 --> 00:32:00,885
After finding Mr. Sakuma,

450
00:32:01,586 --> 00:32:03,354
you went further down the path all alone.

451
00:32:06,124 --> 00:32:06,958
Yes.

452
00:32:10,762 --> 00:32:11,729
Then

453
00:32:13,932 --> 00:32:15,733
I heard another gunshot.

454
00:32:22,140 --> 00:32:23,107
Then what happened?

455
00:32:24,309 --> 00:32:25,777
I hid behind a tree

456
00:32:26,411 --> 00:32:27,946
and peeked out from there,

457
00:32:29,314 --> 00:32:30,615
and saw something blue…

458
00:32:34,385 --> 00:32:35,820
I went further ahead,

459
00:32:38,256 --> 00:32:40,425
and realized it was Officer Kiyohara.

460
00:32:41,492 --> 00:32:42,694
In other words,

461
00:32:42,760 --> 00:32:48,132
you were the first one to discover
Officer Kiyohara's body?

462
00:32:48,633 --> 00:32:50,802
- Yes.
- Please continue.

463
00:32:52,370 --> 00:32:54,105
When I went back to Naoto,

464
00:32:56,541 --> 00:32:58,276
Keisuke and Makiko were there.

465
00:33:00,178 --> 00:33:01,012
That's when

466
00:33:01,813 --> 00:33:06,084
all four of you found out
about Officer Kiyohara, correct?

467
00:33:07,352 --> 00:33:08,186
Yes.

468
00:33:12,390 --> 00:33:13,524
I see.

469
00:33:18,663 --> 00:33:20,465
I have two handkerchiefs here.

470
00:33:21,165 --> 00:33:22,233
Please place one

471
00:33:22,734 --> 00:33:25,470
at the location where Officer Kiyohara
was found lying down.

472
00:33:28,506 --> 00:33:30,041
The other will be placed

473
00:33:31,109 --> 00:33:34,412
at the location where Nobukazu Oshima
was found lying down.

474
00:33:37,515 --> 00:33:39,384
According to the investigation reports,

475
00:33:39,884 --> 00:33:42,286
Officer Kiyohara
was found lying on his back

476
00:33:42,353 --> 00:33:44,856
with a gunshot wound to the heart.

477
00:33:45,523 --> 00:33:48,359
The gun Oshima was holding
when he was found on the ground,

478
00:33:48,426 --> 00:33:49,827
was a modified gun.

479
00:33:51,629 --> 00:33:53,064
Please imagine this.

480
00:33:54,132 --> 00:33:57,568
When Officer Kiyohara
found the culprit in the forest,

481
00:33:58,302 --> 00:34:00,938
he did what any police officer would do,

482
00:34:01,672 --> 00:34:05,209
and first gave a verbal command
for the suspect to stop.

483
00:34:05,276 --> 00:34:07,378
Detective Tobina, please reenact it.

484
00:34:22,260 --> 00:34:23,127
Freeze.

485
00:34:23,995 --> 00:34:25,430
<i>Freeze!</i>

486
00:34:29,400 --> 00:34:30,368
<i>However,</i>

487
00:34:31,035 --> 00:34:32,804
Oshima did not stop.

488
00:34:33,371 --> 00:34:37,175
<i>On the contrary, he fired his gun</i>
<i>at Officer Kiyohara.</i>

489
00:34:38,609 --> 00:34:39,444
Bang.

490
00:34:40,878 --> 00:34:42,213
In response,

491
00:34:42,280 --> 00:34:46,384
Officer Kiyohara fired
a second warning shot.

492
00:34:46,451 --> 00:34:48,219
Drop your gun!

493
00:34:51,756 --> 00:34:55,026
Since no bullet casings were found
near the scene,

494
00:34:55,092 --> 00:34:58,362
it can be concluded that the shots
were not fired with Oshima as the target.

495
00:34:59,530 --> 00:35:00,598
However,

496
00:35:01,933 --> 00:35:05,803
it seems that Officer Kiyohara's decision
backfired.

497
00:35:06,971 --> 00:35:08,005
Undeterred

498
00:35:08,506 --> 00:35:11,109
<i>by the warning shot,</i>

499
00:35:12,543 --> 00:35:18,049
<i>Oshima used the modified gun</i>
<i>to fire at Officer Kiyohara.</i>

500
00:35:19,617 --> 00:35:20,585
<i>And that bullet</i>

501
00:35:21,085 --> 00:35:23,754
<i>hit Officer Kiyohara.</i>

502
00:35:25,323 --> 00:35:27,325
<i>That caused him to fall to the ground.</i>

503
00:35:30,695 --> 00:35:32,296
Hold on a second.

504
00:35:33,598 --> 00:35:34,432
My father

505
00:35:34,932 --> 00:35:38,035
shot Oshima before he fell down,
didn't he?

506
00:35:38,102 --> 00:35:39,604
That's impossible.

507
00:35:42,106 --> 00:35:44,142
If someone were shot at this distance,

508
00:35:44,208 --> 00:35:46,978
most people wouldn't be able
to remain standing.

509
00:35:48,613 --> 00:35:49,614
Then

510
00:35:50,715 --> 00:35:52,850
did my father shoot him
after he had fallen down?

511
00:35:52,917 --> 00:35:54,418
Using all his remaining strength?

512
00:35:54,919 --> 00:35:56,721
He was shot in the heart.

513
00:35:57,221 --> 00:35:59,857
It is believed that he collapsed
and died instantly.

514
00:36:00,525 --> 00:36:01,359
What?

515
00:36:04,529 --> 00:36:05,363
What…

516
00:36:06,464 --> 00:36:10,067
So, does that mean someone else
shot Oshima?

517
00:36:11,169 --> 00:36:12,770
That's the only reasonable conclusion.

518
00:36:17,542 --> 00:36:20,545
Then could it be the accomplice?

519
00:36:21,312 --> 00:36:25,416
Did the accomplice shoot Oshima to keep
the 30 million yen?

520
00:36:25,917 --> 00:36:27,852
That's one possibility.

521
00:36:27,919 --> 00:36:30,388
What other possibilities are there?

522
00:36:32,823 --> 00:36:35,059
When you all arrived at the scene,

523
00:36:35,593 --> 00:36:39,630
Officer Kiyohara's gun
was already missing.

524
00:36:40,631 --> 00:36:41,799
That's correct, isn't it?

525
00:36:43,067 --> 00:36:44,001
Yes.

526
00:36:44,068 --> 00:36:45,269
It was not there.

527
00:36:47,171 --> 00:36:48,339
Let's assume

528
00:36:48,839 --> 00:36:53,411
that the accomplice
ran off with Officer Kiyohara's gun.

529
00:36:54,278 --> 00:36:56,214
What would be the reason for that?

530
00:36:56,280 --> 00:36:58,149
The only thing I can think of
is fingerprints.

531
00:36:59,550 --> 00:37:01,519
If there was an accomplice

532
00:37:01,586 --> 00:37:04,789
and that person killed Oshima
with Officer Kiyohara's gun,

533
00:37:06,557 --> 00:37:09,560
the accomplice's fingerprints
would be left on the gun.

534
00:37:13,397 --> 00:37:16,000
Maybe the accomplice took the gun
for that reason?

535
00:37:16,067 --> 00:37:17,168
I see.

536
00:37:17,235 --> 00:37:19,237
It makes sense logically.

537
00:37:19,904 --> 00:37:20,972
But I'm sure

538
00:37:21,672 --> 00:37:24,408
the accomplice was prepared
not to leave fingerprints behind.

539
00:37:25,943 --> 00:37:28,179
When I checked the photos in the reports,

540
00:37:28,246 --> 00:37:31,549
Oshima was wearing gloves on both hands.

541
00:37:32,049 --> 00:37:33,484
If he had an accomplice,

542
00:37:33,551 --> 00:37:37,121
that person
must have also had gloves on too.

543
00:37:38,456 --> 00:37:41,325
The reason why
the accomplice took the gun…

544
00:37:41,959 --> 00:37:44,061
The more I think about it,

545
00:37:44,128 --> 00:37:46,297
the more I don't understand.

546
00:37:47,798 --> 00:37:50,601
Officer Kiyohara's gun is,

547
00:37:51,335 --> 00:37:54,372
of course, the standard issue gun
of the Japanese police.

548
00:37:55,373 --> 00:37:58,376
Even if someone were to steal it,
they wouldn't be able to use it again.

549
00:37:58,442 --> 00:38:00,845
Since it can be identified immediately.

550
00:38:02,280 --> 00:38:05,783
It was a gun that was pointless
to make off with.

551
00:38:06,284 --> 00:38:08,619
So I started to think…

552
00:38:09,520 --> 00:38:15,259
Maybe the accomplice didn't actually
make off with the gun?

553
00:38:16,460 --> 00:38:17,595
In other words,

554
00:38:18,529 --> 00:38:21,265
maybe the gun was still on the ground

555
00:38:21,866 --> 00:38:24,802
near Officer Kiyohara's body?

556
00:38:26,971 --> 00:38:28,005
The question is,

557
00:38:29,340 --> 00:38:31,442
who shot Oshima?

558
00:38:32,510 --> 00:38:33,611
That's the real mystery.

559
00:38:37,214 --> 00:38:39,016
Officer Kiyohara

560
00:38:39,784 --> 00:38:41,452
was shot by Oshima

561
00:38:41,519 --> 00:38:43,421
and died on the spot.

562
00:38:45,056 --> 00:38:46,290
When he was shot,

563
00:38:47,558 --> 00:38:50,961
<i>he dropped the gun he was holding.</i>

564
00:38:52,463 --> 00:38:55,733
The person who picked it up shot Oshima.

565
00:38:58,069 --> 00:38:59,236
So…

566
00:39:00,237 --> 00:39:02,340
who shot Oshima?

567
00:39:04,475 --> 00:39:06,410
In this situation,

568
00:39:07,144 --> 00:39:09,547
it narrows down the pool of suspects.

569
00:39:11,315 --> 00:39:12,416
For example,

570
00:39:14,652 --> 00:39:17,288
the first person
to arrive at this location.

571
00:39:24,128 --> 00:39:25,096
Detective,

572
00:39:25,596 --> 00:39:28,599
are you trying to say
that Junichi shot him?

573
00:39:30,501 --> 00:39:31,969
That's impossible.

574
00:39:32,036 --> 00:39:33,604
We were just elementary school students.

575
00:39:34,171 --> 00:39:36,607
There's no way we could have fired a gun.

576
00:39:38,342 --> 00:39:39,710
My father,

577
00:39:40,578 --> 00:39:41,979
Officer Kiyohara,

578
00:39:42,947 --> 00:39:45,416
was involved in a shootout with Oshima.

579
00:39:57,294 --> 00:39:58,129
Junichi?

580
00:40:07,872 --> 00:40:09,173
<i>Keisuke, you should go with her.</i>

581
00:40:09,874 --> 00:40:10,708
What?

582
00:40:11,609 --> 00:40:12,777
Take care of Makiko.

583
00:40:13,844 --> 00:40:14,845
Okay.

584
00:40:17,681 --> 00:40:18,682
Naoto!

585
00:40:24,021 --> 00:40:25,189
I'll go check things out.

586
00:40:26,424 --> 00:40:27,558
You stay here.

587
00:40:27,625 --> 00:40:28,893
No, I'll go with you.

588
00:40:30,127 --> 00:40:31,128
Don't overdo it.

589
00:41:03,060 --> 00:41:04,028
Pops.

590
00:42:15,232 --> 00:42:16,634
I shot him.

591
00:43:35,980 --> 00:43:37,581
<i>Keep in touch even after you move.</i>

592
00:43:37,648 --> 00:43:38,716
<i>I won't.</i>

593
00:43:43,287 --> 00:43:45,055
- Why?
- Just shut up.

594
00:43:47,958 --> 00:43:49,493
<i>You shouldn't be</i>

595
00:43:50,995 --> 00:43:52,529
with someone like me!

596
00:44:00,671 --> 00:44:02,306
The person who killed Oshima…

597
00:44:04,375 --> 00:44:05,442
was me.

598
00:44:12,950 --> 00:44:15,686
That doesn't mean
I can continue being a police officer.

599
00:44:15,753 --> 00:44:18,822
I think you became a police officer
because you committed a crime.

600
00:44:18,889 --> 00:44:19,757
THE FINAL CULPRIT IS IDENTIFIED

601
00:44:19,823 --> 00:44:21,458
<i>I'm a suspect, aren't I?</i>

602
00:44:21,525 --> 00:44:23,560
<i>Junichi, do you think Makiko did it?</i>

603
00:44:23,627 --> 00:44:25,663
I can't undo the fact…

604
00:44:25,729 --> 00:44:26,997
<i>that I have committed a crime.</i>

605
00:44:27,064 --> 00:44:27,898
CAN SOMEONE WHO COMMITTED A CRIME
BE FORGIVEN?

606
00:44:27,965 --> 00:44:28,866
Subtitle translation by: Lili Morita
